X86_64 Processor Features
[=========================]

Overview
>--------<
This module provides comprehensive x86_64 processor feature detection and manipulation,
including CPUID queries, register access, and low-level CPU instructions.


Features
---====---

1. CPU Identification (CPUID)
----------------------------

Detect processor vendor, model, family, and features:
  - Processor vendor string
  - Brand name
  - CPU signature (Family, Model, Stepping)
  - Feature flags (SSE, AVX, AES, VMX, etc.)
  - Hypervisor detection
  - Cache line size

2. Control Registers
--------------------

Access x86_64 control registers:
  - CR0 (paging, protected mode, caching)
  - CR2 (page fault address)
  - CR3 (page directory base)
  - CR4 (extended features)
  - RFLAGS (status flags)

3. Model-Specific Registers (MSR)
--------------------------------

Read/write MSRs for:
  - Time Stamp Counter (TSC)
  - APIC configuration
  - Performance counters
  - Thermal monitoring
  - Power management

4. Instructions
---------------

Low-level CPU instructions:
  - Interrupt control (CLI, STI)
  - Memory barriers (LFENCE, MFENCE, SFENCE)
  - Cache operations (CLFLUSH, PREFETCH)
  - Atomic operations (LOCK XADD)
  - Bit scan operations (BSF, BSR)
  - Serialization (CPUID, PAUSE)

5. Memory Management
----------------------

Page table structures and operations:
  - Page table entry (PTE) flags
  - TLB invalidation
  - Physical address translation
  - Memory attribute control (PAT)

6. Segmentation
---------------

GDT, IDT, and TSS structures:
  - Global Descriptor Table entries
  - Interrupt Descriptor Table entries
  - Task State Segment
  - Segment selectors and privilege levels

Examples
===-====

Detect CPU Features:

  #include "x86_cpuinfo.h"

  x86_cpuinfo_t info;
  x86_get_cpuinfo(&info);

  if (info.has_avx) {
      printf("AVX supported\n");
  }

  x86_print_cpuinfo(&info);

Read Control Registers
----------------------

  #include "x86_registers.h"

  x86_control_regs_t regs;
  x86_get_control_regs(&regs);

  printf("Paging enabled: %s\n", (regs.cr0 & CR0_PG) ? "yes" : "no");
  x86_print_control_regs(&regs);


Timing with TSC
---------------
  #include "x86_intrinsics.h"

  x86_cpuid_barrier();          // Serialize
  uint64_t start = x86_read_tsc();

  // Code to measure
  for (int i = 0; i < 1000; i++) {
      // Work here
  }

  uint64_t end = x86_read_tsc();
  printf("Cycles: %lu\n", end - start);


Cache Operations
----------------

  char buffer[4096];

  x86_prefetch0(buffer);        // Prefetch into L1
  // Use buffer
  x86_clflush(buffer);          // Flush from cache


Atomic Operations
--------------------

  volatile uint64_t counter = 0;

  x86_atomic_inc(&counter);     // Atomic increment
  x86_atomic_add(&counter, 100);// Atomic add

Compilation
===========
Ensure assembly files are compiled:

  ASMFLAGS = -nostdlib -no-pie -fPIC
  CFLAGS = -O2 -march=native

Platform Requirement
--------------------
  - x86_64 architecture
  - Linux/Unix-like OS
  - GCC or Clang compiler
  - AS (GNU Assembler)

Notes
-----
  - Some operations require kernel mode or elevated privileges
  - TSC is not guaranteed to be synchronized across cores
  - Register operations are CPU-specific and volatile
  - Always use barriers when measuring timing-sensitive code

